article.description:
Josh Howard had 23 points as  the Mavericks beat the Sonics 110-91 Saturday night
for their 11th straight victory, matching the NBA's longest winning
streak this season.
article.headline: Mavs' 11-game streak matches NBA's season best
article.linkText: Mavericks beat Sonics for 11th straight win
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks have used a new formula while matching the NBA's longest winning streak this season. They've done it with defense and without Dirk Nowitzki as their leading scorer every night. Josh Howard had 23 points to lead Dallas in scoring for the fourth straight game, and the Mavs beat Seattle 110-91 Saturday night for their 11th straight victory. "I'm in a good groove, my teammates are finding me and I feel confident," Howard said. "We're playing as a team and we wanted to keep this streak alive." Dallas' winning streak coincides with its franchise-record stretch of holding 11 straight opponents under 100 points. Seattle came in second in the NBA with 102.3 points per game, but also was coming off a 100-77 loss at Houston the night before. "You can tell they're a better defensive team," said Rashard Lewis, held to nine points on 1-of-11 shooting. "They took me out. I couldn't get anything rolling." At 37-10 under coach Avery Johnson in his first full season, the Mavericks matched San Antonio atop the Southwest Division with the best record in the Western Conference. Nowitzki, the team's leading scorer at 25.6 points a game, has led Dallas in scoring just once in the last seven games. He wasn't even in when the Mavs made their push against Seattle that finally put it out of reach. When Nowitzki took a breather late in the third quarter, Dallas led 73-68. By the time he returned with 9:24 left, the lead had been stretched to 92-78. "We got a lot of depth, a lot of guys can put the ball in the hole," Jason Terry said. "Dirk's still No. 1, but if he isn't scoring, we've got other guys that can pick up the slack." Things were going so good for the Mavs during that spurt that a deflection wound up in Terry's hands in the left corner, and he hit a 3-pointer that made it 88-74. On the next possession, Jerry Stackhouse penetrated then passed out to Devin Harris for an open jumper. Terry finished with 22 points, while Nowitzki (8-of-19 shooting) and Stackhouse had 17 each. Erick Dampier, coming off the bench for the 11th straight game after starting the first 36, had 11 points and 14 rebounds. He played 27 minutes, more than usual because of DeSagana Diop's foul trouble. "It speaks to the depth of our team. Guys are going to have off nights," Stackhouse said. "Dirk's going to deliver more often than not, but it's good that he doesn't feel pressure every night to score 25 or 30 points." Ray Allen led Seattle with 17 points. Lewis, who was averaging 22 points and had made 60-of-110 shots (55 percent) the last 10 games, missed his first nine shots before a fastbreak reverse layup got the SuperSonics within 71-68 in the third quarter. They never got closer, as Howard hit a field goal and made a free throw right after that. Detroit had an 11-game winning streak snapped Tuesday at New Jersey. The next night at Memphis, the Mavericks overcame a 10-point deficit in the fourth quarter and won 81-80 after Nowitzki hit two free throws with 7.2 seconds left. Next up for Dallas are Kobe Bryant and the Los Angeles Lakers on Tuesday night, the second of nine home games the Mavericks will play over the next 10 games. Bryant scored 62 points against the Mavs on Dec. 20 in Los Angeles without playing the fourth quarter, and had 43 points in Dallas a week before that. The game against the Sonics was tied at 12 midway through the first quarter when a frustrated coach Johnson called timeout. Howard hit a 10-foot jumper out the timeout, starting a 20-2 run that put the Mavs ahead to stay. Howard and Terry had consecutive 3-pointers after Seattle's only basket in that spurt that put Dallas ahead 32-14.

Game notes
The Mavs have won six in a row against Seattle, their longest streak in the series since winning seven in a row from April 1986 through November 1987. Seattle has been held below 100 points in all the games. ... Seattle got within 54-51 by halftime, and was down only 56-55 after Vladimir Radmanovic made a 3-pointer early in the third quarter. Nowitzki then extended the lead by tipping his own miss twice before it finally went in. ... The Sonics are 6-14 when playing back-to-back games.
